picam-orchestrator (1.0.0+202606221547) stable; urgency=medium

  * Major restructure: removed the separate "Annotated" stream.
    Annotation (delay + detection boxes) is now an orthogonal,
    independently toggleable flag on EITHER resolution (Lores or
    Main), not a third stream of its own. StreamSource is now just
    {Lores, Main}.
  * Each resolution has its own delay buffer (mainDelayBuf,
    loresDelayBuf), always drained regardless of whether annotation
    is currently on, so flipping the toggle doesn't have to wait for
    the buffer to refill before the first delayed frame is ready. A
    client's existing connection seamlessly switches between live and
    delayed+annotated when the flag changes — no reconnect needed.
  * New GET /annotate?lores=true|false&main=true|false — independent
    per-resolution toggles, global per-Pi (same viewer-of-that-
    resolution-sees-the-same-thing model as the OSD toggle), no
    restart needed. New config keys annotate.lores / annotate.main
    (each default false) set the startup state.
  * /status.json now reports lores_annotated and main_annotated
    instead of a streams.annotated client count.
  * Verified end-to-end against a real picam-raw protocol emulator:
    connected a live Main viewer, toggled main annotation on mid-
    stream, and confirmed the SAME connection kept receiving frames
    (now delayed) with no reconnect — then connected Lores
    independently and confirmed its own annotation state stayed
    unaffected by Main's.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 15:47:26 +0000

picam-orchestrator (1.0.0+202606221012) stable; urgency=medium

  * Split the OSD burn-in into two independent toggles: camera ID
    (bottom-left) and timestamp (bottom-right) can now be enabled or
    disabled separately, instead of one combined flag controlling
    both. New config keys osd.camera_id and osd.time (each default
    false) replace osd.enabled as the startup defaults.
  * GET /osd now accepts independent ?camera_id=true|false and
    &time=true|false params. The legacy ?enabled=true|false is still
    accepted for backward compatibility and sets both flags together.
  * /status.json now reports camera_id_enabled and time_enabled
    separately, replacing the single osd_enabled field.
  * Verified by rendering all four enable/disable combinations
    directly (both on, camera-id-only, time-only, both off) and
    confirming each produces exactly the expected pixels with no
    leftover background boxes from the disabled element. Also
    verified the full three-tier HTTP chain: toggling one flag
    through picam-frontend's proxy correctly leaves the other
    untouched, confirmed by querying the backend directly.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 10:12:18 +0000

picam-orchestrator (1.0.0+202606220935) stable; urgency=medium

  * Changed default http_port from 80 to 81. Resolves the port
    collision with picam-frontend (also defaulting to 80) when both
    run on the same machine — the exact scenario that caused
    picam-frontend to silently lose the bind() race and listen on a
    random ephemeral port instead (fixed in the previous release).
    Now the two services have non-overlapping defaults out of the
    box: picam-orchestrator on 81, picam-frontend on 80.
  * Updated all doc comments, startup log messages, config.ini, the
    systemd service file's capability-grant comment, and postinst's
    printed URLs to reflect port 81.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 09:35:47 +0000

picam-orchestrator (1.0.0+202606220931) stable; urgency=high

  * Fixed the same unchecked-bind() bug found and fixed in
    picam-frontend: MjpegHttpServer::start() and StatusServer::loop()
    both ignored bind()'s return value, meaning a port conflict
    (e.g. with another instance, or any other process already using
    http_port/status_port) silently moved the listening socket to a
    random ephemeral port while still logging the configured port as
    if everything were fine. MjpegHttpServer now logs a FATAL message
    with the OS error and exits with status 1; StatusServer (which
    runs on a detached thread) logs the same FATAL and just stops
    that one server rather than killing the whole process.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 09:31:14 +0000

picam-orchestrator (1.0.0+202606220901) stable; urgency=low

  * Renamed from picam-stream to picam-orchestrator (package, binary,
    paths, service, config directory all updated). Reflects that this
    package now does more than stream — it also proxies OSD toggling
    and camera switching to picam-raw, "orchestrating" the pipeline
    rather than just relaying frames.
  * Updated package description and systemd service description to
    mention all four capabilities (streaming, status, OSD, camera
    switch) instead of just streaming.

