picam-stream (1.0.0+202606220858) stable; urgency=low

  * Added GET /camera?id=N — switches picam-raw's active camera by
    proxying to its existing CommandServer protocol ("switch<N>\n" on
    TCP port 8556 by default, configurable via telemetry.command_port).
    Lets picam-frontend offer a camera-switch button without speaking
    picam-raw's plain-text TCP protocol directly — it only ever talks
    HTTP to picam-stream. Response passes through picam-raw's own
    JSON verbatim (ok/active_camera/label or ok:false/error), with
    the HTTP status distinguishing reach-failures (502) from
    picam-raw successfully responding (200, even for a rejected
    switch like an unconfigured camera index).
  * Verified end-to-end with a fake picam-raw CommandServer
    implementing the real protocol: confirmed successful switches,
    rejected invalid camera indices, and missing ?id= all produce the
    correct HTTP status and JSON body.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 08:58:40 +0000

picam-stream (1.0.0+202606220805) stable; urgency=low

  * Added frame_ts_us to /status.json — the embedded timestamp (Unix
    microseconds) from the most recently encoded frame, taken from
    picam-raw's own clock as carried in every UDP chunk-0 header. This
    is NOT this Pi's or the viewer's wall-clock time. Lets the web UI
    show the camera feed's actual time instead of guessing from local
    clocks. PipelineStatus (already tracking frames_in/out/clients)
    moved earlier in the file so MjpegHttpServer's /status.json
    handler can read latest_frame_ts_us from it directly.
  * Verified end-to-end with a protocol-correct fake picam-raw backend
    (replies to the HELLO registration ping, as real picam-raw does)
    sending frames stamped with a deliberately distinctive timestamp
    (2030-01-01) — confirmed it round-trips correctly through
    /status.json's frame_ts_us field exactly as sent.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 08:05:04 +0000

picam-stream (1.0.0+202606220744) stable; urgency=high

  * Added on-the-fly OSD toggle: GET /osd?enabled=true|false flips the
    camera-ID/timestamp burn-in instantly, no config edit or restart
    needed. Global per-Pi — affects every connected viewer and every
    stream (Main/Lores/Annotated). osd.enabled in config.ini is now
    only the startup default; the running state is tracked in a
    global atomic and can change at any time via the new endpoint.
  * /status.json now reports osd_enabled so any UI can show current
    state without guessing.
  * Fixed a clean-shutdown hang in UdpRawReceiver: its UDP socket had
    no SO_RCVTIMEO, so recvLoop's recv() call could block forever
    whenever picam-raw went quiet. close()ing the socket from the
    destructor does not reliably unblock a thread already parked
    inside recv() on a UDP socket — confirmed via gdb thread dump:
    main() was stuck in ~UdpRawReceiver()'s join() with the recv
    thread still sitting in recv(). Fixed with the same 1s timeout
    pattern already used for DetectionReceiver/TelemetryReceiver.
    Verified: shutdown went from hanging past 30+ seconds to exiting
    within 2 seconds.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 07:44:38 +0000

picam-stream (1.0.0+202606220727) stable; urgency=low

  * Added an optional OSD burn-in: camera ID (bottom-left) + wall-clock
    timestamp (bottom-right) drawn directly into the video frame pixels
    via the same 5x7 bitmap font already used by the detection-box
    annotator. Applies to all three streams (main, lores, annotated).
    Off by default — enable via [osd] enabled=true in config.ini.
  * Camera labels are configurable per index (osd.camera_labels =
    Front,Back) for readability; falls back to the bare numeric index
    if unset.
  * Verified with a standalone pixel-level test: confirmed the burn-in
    only touches the intended bottom-left/bottom-right corner regions
    and leaves the rest of the frame (including the exact center)
    completely untouched.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 07:15:00 +0000

picam-stream (1.0.0+202606200640) stable; urgency=high

  * Fixed a clean-shutdown bug found while testing picam-frontend's
    proxy logic against this same accept-loop pattern: close()ing the
    listening socket does NOT reliably unblock another thread that is
    parked inside accept() on that fd. Confirmed via gdb — the accept
    thread stayed in accept() even after close() ran, leaving the
    destructor's acceptThread_.join() to hang forever. Fixed by calling
    shutdown(fd, SHUT_RDWR) before close() — shutdown() does force a
    blocked accept() call to return with an error.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 06:45:00 +0000

picam-stream (1.0.0+202606200626) stable; urgency=low

  * Renamed from picam-web to picam-stream and split into a headless
    backend with no web UI of its own. Removed the / and /index.html
    HTML-serving routes entirely — this package now serves only
    /stream?stream=main|lores|annotated and /status.json.
  * Install picam-frontend on a separate machine (or any one Pi) to
    get a browser interface that can view and switch between multiple
    picam-stream backends from a single page.
  * Carries forward the lock-free client-list redesign from picam-web:
    the hot per-frame encode loop never touches a mutex when reading
    the connected-client list, eliminating the lock-contention hangs
    chased through several earlier picam-web releases.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 06:26:24 +0000
